04736nam a22006375i 9781847792310DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132007xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818477923107 a10.7765/97818477923102doi  a(DE-B1597)660169  a(OCoLC)960758600  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a341.24221 aRadaelli, Claudio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRegulatory quality in Europe :bConcepts, measures and policy processes /cFabrizio De Francesco, Claudio Radaelli. 1aManchester : bManchester University Press, c[2013] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEuropean Politics00tFront matter -- tDedication -- tContents -- tList of tables, boxes and figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Appraising regulatory policy -- t2 Defining quality -- t3 How indicators perform -- t4 Measuring the performance of better regulation policies -- t5 The results of the questionnaire -- t6 The state of play in the EU -- t7 Better regulation indicators -- t8 Conclusion -- tAppendix 1 -- tAppendix 2 -- tAppendix 3 -- tAppendix 4 -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe European Union and its member states are investing in ambitious programmes for ‘better regulation’ and targets of regulatory quality. This book, available in paperback for the first time, lifts the veil of excessively optimistic propositions covering the whole better regulation agenda. It provides an innovative conceptual framework to handle the political complexity of regulatory governance. It approaches better regulation as an emerging public policy, with its own political context, actors, problems, rules of interaction, instruments, activities and impacts. Focusing on the key tools of impact assessment, consultation, simplification, and access to legislation, the authors provide fresh empirical evidence on the progress made in the member states and in Brussels, drawing on an extensive research project and an original survey of directors of better regulation programmes in Europe. Radaelli and De Francesco show how indicators define, measure, and appraise better regulation policy, linking measures to policy processes in which the stakeholders learn by monitoring. Although better regulation is a top priority for competitiveness in Europe and the legitimacy of EU policy, the level of commitment and the development of tools vary considerably. The major challenge for better regulation is institutionalisation - this calls for clear choices in terms of what the EU wants from better regulation.Essential reading for academics (political scientists, lawyers, and public economists) and policy-makers in charge of regulatory reforms in governments and international organisations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh  aEuropean Union.  abetter regulation.  aconsultation.  aimpact assessment.  amember states.  apublic policy.  aregulatory governance.  aregulatory quality.  arules of interaction.  asimplification.1 aDe Francesco, Fabrizio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDe Francesco, Fabrizio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadaelli, Claudio M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779231040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792310/original